<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>Notice that when an alarm clock breaks, its repair requires taking the physical stance.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>(For variety Dennett mentions the astrological stance.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>The second is called the design stance.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>The first he calls the physical stance.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>The third is called the intentional stance, and this is what we'll often need for understanding computer programs.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>Daniel Dennett, Tufts University philosopher, has proposed three attitudes aimed at understanding a system with which one interacts.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>The design stance is appropriate not only for machinery but also for the parts of an organism.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>Dennett's example of this is the alarm clock.</a>
<a name="8">[8]</a> <a href="#8" id=8>With the automatic teller, things are a little less clear.</a>
<a name="9">[9]</a> <a href="#9" id=9>In this we look at the system in terms of its physical structure at various levels of organization.</a>
